  "doc_id": "33815",
  "text": "In one study, Tobias Härle et al. [CITATION_1] assessed the accuracy of the IFR prospectively in more than 100 patients with borderline coronary lesions; the IFR correlated strongly with the FFR (r s = 0.81; P < 0.0001). ROC analysis showed an area under the curve (AUC) equals 0.9106, suggesting the high reliability of the IFR as an accurate diagnostic test. The IFR-only technique with a treatment cut-point ≤ 0.89 revealed a diagnostic agreement with the FFR-only technique strategy in more than 120 lesions (nearly 83%) with a sensitivity of nearly 80%, a specificity of 86%. In another study, Alfredo Fede et al. [CITATION_2] included more than 50 patients with borderline lesions and there was close agreement between the FFR and the IFR (R = 0.83, P < 0.0001). Deep Chandh Raja et al. [CITATION_3] found that IFR correlated with FFR in all the subgroups and across all the vessels, without any influence for the heart rate or blood pressure on the correlation with FFR. Also, there are some meta-analysis studies that addressed this point and clarified this concordance.",
